A Classic British comedy series that never gets too dull to watch over and over! If you like British comedy you have to check out the Carry On series.

This is just an informational review. This set is a great continuation of what started with The Carry On Collection back in 2002. Here are the movies in CARRY ON COLLECTION VOL 1, 8 movie set (plus the listed bonus features): DON'T LOSE YOUR HEAD (1966) ("Carry on laughing until you have hysterics, but DON'T LOSE YOUR HEAD") FOLLOW THAT CAMEL (1967) ("Bilko joins the Carry On Legion") CARRY ON DOCTOR (1967) CARRY ON UP THE KHYBER (1968) CARRY ON CAMPING (1969) CARRY ON AGAIN DOCTOR (1969) CARRY ON UP THE JUNGLE (1970) -Audio Commentary With Jackie Piper & Valerie Leon -Trailer -Stills Gallery -Carry On Trivia CARRY ON LOVING (1970) -Audio Commentary With Richard O'Callaghan & Jackie Piper -Trailer -Stills Gallery -Carry On Trivia NOTE: Carry On Collection Vol 2 is also available.
Oldie but a goodie

A collection of some of the the carry-on films. They must be experienced to be understood, and repeated viewing and familiarity with the ensemble cast enhances enjoyment. They contain occasional awful moments but are still some of the very best of British humor. Up there with Fawlty Towers and Monty Python. Possibly even better.
Love the British humour.  Loved it.

Need a laugh on a bad day? I put one of these on and a smile instantly comes to my face. Silly and antiquated, but classic and simply delightful. I hope another generation picks up the brand name and relaunches this series.

Brilliant, wonderful and quite splendid. The 'Carry On' comedy film series (and this is only a small slice) is a part of British cinematic film history. If you are in need of anti-political-correctness medication, then self prescribe yourself a dose of these movies. This is proof why the British (and Irish) have the best sense of humor in the entire universe.

Oh how we adore these movies! I grew up on the Carry On series although didn't get to see them all!  Kenneth Williams was always my firm favorite and wished he appeared in all of them (although he appears in most).  This collection contains;  Carry On Camel, Don't Lose Your Head (a hilarious take on the French Revolution), Up The Khyber (a great humorous take at the British Khyber Pass era), Doctor, Camping, Again Doctor, Jungle and Carry On Loving.  All are excellent with Carry on Follow That Camel being a hilarious take on The Four Feathers.  Many regulars who appeared in most if not all the Carry On films are favorites such as Kenneth Williams, Kenneth Connor, Charles Hawtrey (a real life character), Sid James (always a lovable favorite and quite the ladies man in films and out), Frankie Howard, Joan Sims, Hattie Jacques, Jim Dale, Angela Douglas, Liz Fraser (who also appeared in a Rumpole episode), Barbara Windsor (an adorable blond who in real life had a long term relationship with Sid James), Bernard Bresslaw (a most talented comic who was lost to us far too soon).  Perhaps three of the Carry On series were less than stellar with Carry On Columbus easily being the worst.  Carry On England has its merits and is enjoyable albeit it lacking in creativity and storyline. Carry On Emmanuele wasn't quite as bad as critics' remarks about it.  Each one of course is loaded with double entendres with almost every sentence containing at least one sexual reference some not so vague as well as creatively funny observances and uses of the English language.  They don't make 'em like this anymore!
full of double entendres from start to finish. Hilarious wit at it's British best.
